id="post-1612" class="hentry p1 post publish author-drew category-dessert tag-chocolate tag-thanksgiving comments-open pings-open y2008 m06 d12 h11 slug-frozen-chocolate-truffle-pie"><h1 class="entry-title">Frozen Chocolate Truffle Pie</h1><div
class="entry-meta"><span
class="meta-prep meta-prep-author">By </span><span
class="author vcard"><a
class="url fn n" href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/author/drook/" title="View all posts by Drew">Drew</a></span><span
class="meta-sep meta-sep-entry-date"> | </span><span
class="meta-prep meta-prep-entry-date">Published: </span><span
class="entry-date"><abbr
class="published" title="2008-06-12T11:21:00-0400">June 12, 2008</abbr></span></div><div
class="entry-content"><p><img
class="hero-pic" src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-201650_Med.jpg"></p><p>If you don&#8217;t like chocolate, stop reading right now. If you like &#8220;a little chocolate now and then,&#8221; go away. This recipe is for <em>serious</em> chocolate fiends only.</p><p>Imagine the darkest, richest truffle you&#8217;ve ever had. Now imagine taking more than a pound of the centers and pouring it into a pie shell. &#8216;Cause that&#8217;s about what this recipe is. This fall when it&#8217;s cooler, I&#8217;ll do my chocolate truffles and you&#8217;ll see how close the recipes are. Until then, trust me that this will be the most <em>ridiculously</em> rich chocolate pie you&#8217;ve ever tasted.<br
/> <span
id="more-1612"></span></p><h3>Ingredients</h3><p><a
target="_NEW" href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-122050_Lg.jpg" rel="lightbox[1612]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-122050_Sm.jpg" width="240" height="180" align="right"></a><br
/> 12 ounces bitter sweet or semi sweet chocolate<br
/> 1-1/2 sticks butter<br
/> 6 large egg whites<br
/> 4 large egg yolks<br
/> 3 tablespoons cocoa<br
/> 1/3 cup sugar<br
/> pinch of salt<br
/> pinch cream of tartar<br
/> <a
target="_NEW" href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/2008/06/how-to-make-pre-baked-pie-crust/">pre-baked pie crust</a></p><div
style="clear:both;"></div><h3>Directions</h3><p>Before I get started, I wanted to mention this recipe was featured on the Lexiophiles 2009 International Recipe Advent Calendar. You can check that out for lots of other great holiday recipes.</p><p><a
target="_NEW" href="http://www.lexiophiles.com/featured-article/international-recipe-advent-calendar-2009"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/images/lexiophiles-adv-cal-05.png" width="400" height="120"></a></p><p>Now on with the recipe &#8230;</p><p>Make a double boiler by bringing a half pan of water to a boil, turning the heat to low, and setting a large stainless bowl over it.</p><p><a
target="_NEW" href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-121553_Lg.jpg" rel="lightbox[1612]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-121553_Sm.jpg" width="240" height="180"></a></p><p>Even if you already have a double boiler, do it this way. You&#8217;ll be able to mix everything in this one bowl and save on clean-up.</p><p>Put the butter in the bowl, and once it&#8217;s melted add the chocolate, cocoa, sugar and salt.</p><p><a
target="_NEW" href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-122519_Lg.jpg" rel="lightbox[1612]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-122519_Sm.jpg" width="240" height="180"></a> <a
target="_NEW" href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-123439_Lg.jpg" rel="lightbox[1612]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-123439_Sm.jpg" width="240" height="180"></a></p><blockquote><p><strong>Ingredient notes:</strong> I used half <a
target="_NEW" href="http://www.ghirardelli.com/products/chips_bittersweet.aspx">bittersweet</a> and half <a
target="_NEW" href="http://www.ghirardelli.com/products/chips_semisweet.aspx">semi-sweet</a> chips, both Ghirardelli. You can find them in the baking section at some grocery stores. They&#8217;re the best domestic chocolate I&#8217;ve tried. (And I&#8217;m not saying that just because I&#8217;m a chocolate snob. Try them for yourself.)</p><p>And for the sugar, I decided to use raw instead of white. Just because I saw it in the cupboard and decided to give it a shot. More on this below.</p></blockquote><p>While the chocolate melts, separate the eggs (see <a
target="_NEW" href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/blog/2008/04/tuna-puffs/">here</a> for tips). If you&#8217;re thinking ahead, you&#8217;ll set aside the two extra yolks to make mayonnaise once you&#8217;re done with this. If you&#8217;re distracted, or just don&#8217;t feel like it, don&#8217;t feel bad about dumping them. Eggs are cheap. They&#8217;ll make more.</p><p><a
target="_NEW" href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-123614_Lg.jpg" rel="lightbox[1612]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-123614_Sm.jpg" width="240" height="180"></a></p><p>Start mixing the chocolate and butter together as soon as you see the chips start to melt.</p><p><a
target="_NEW" href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-123756_Lg.jpg" rel="lightbox[1612]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-123756_Sm.jpg" width="240" height="180"></a></p><p>If you&#8217;ve never melted chocolate before, you might want to separate the eggs first so you aren&#8217;t distracted. When the chocolate is completely melted, and the sugar and cocoa are incorporated, remove it from the heat and mix the yolks in one at a time.</p><p><a
target="_NEW" href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-130019_Lg.jpg" rel="lightbox[1612]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-130019_Sm.jpg" width="240" height="180"></a></p><p>Set the chocolate mixture aside and let it cool to room temperature. While it&#8217;s cooling, add the cream of tartar to the egg whites and beat until it forms stiff peaks.</p><p><a
target="_NEW" href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-153039_Lg.jpg" rel="lightbox[1612]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-153039_Sm.jpg" width="240" height="180"></a> <a
target="_NEW" href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-153305_Lg.jpg" rel="lightbox[1612]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-153305_Sm.jpg" width="240" height="180"></a></p><p>For the first minute the egg whites will just foam up a little. Then all at once they&#8217;ll turn pure white and look like a whole different food.</p><p><a
target="_NEW" href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-153340_Lg.jpg" rel="lightbox[1612]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-153340_Med.jpg" width="500" height="375"></a></p><p>Congratulations, you just made meringue. Add about a third of the meringue to the chocolate and mix it in. Then add the rest and fold it in gently.</p><p><a
target="_NEW" href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-153539_Lg.jpg" rel="lightbox[1612]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-153539_Sm.jpg" width="240" height="180"></a> <a
target="_NEW" href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-153713_Lg.jpg" rel="lightbox[1612]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-153713_Sm.jpg" width="240" height="180"></a></p><p>Try not to deflate the eggs while folding. Once the meringue is completely incorporated, pour the mixture into a <a
target="_NEW" href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/blog/2008/06/how-to-make-pre-baked-pie-cust/">pre-baked pie crust</a>.</p><p><a
target="_NEW" href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-153827_Lg.jpg" rel="lightbox[1612]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-153827_Sm.jpg" width="240" height="180"></a> <a
target="_NEW" href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-153936_Lg.jpg" rel="lightbox[1612]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-153936_Sm.jpg" width="240" height="180"></a></p><p>Spread the chocolate evenly. If you&#8217;re fussy about this stuff (like <a
target="_NEW" href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/tarte-tatin/080517-221635_Lg.jpg" rel="lightbox[1612]">I am</a>), make sure the top looks nice.</p><p><a
target="_NEW" href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-154436_Lg.jpg" rel="lightbox[1612]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-154436_Med.jpg" width="500" height="375"></a><br
/><blockquote><strong>Remember when I mentioned the raw sugar?</strong> You can see a little bit of a speckled texture on the surface. Because raw sugar isn&#8217;t ground as fine as refined white, it didn&#8217;t completely dissolve in the melted chocolate. Once it&#8217;s frozen, you&#8217;ll barely notice the difference. As it thaws you&#8217;ll notice a slight crispy granularity. Personally, I liked it, but if you&#8217;re expecting silky-smoothness you&#8217;d be better off using powdered sugar. I heard in a comment below that even refined white sugar still left a bit of graininess.</p></blockquote><p>Freeze for at least two hours, four would be better. Cut with a very sharp knife, not a pie spatula. Serve with fresh whipped cream.</p><p><a
target="_NEW" href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-201650_Lg.jpg" rel="lightbox[1612]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/chocolate-truffle-pie/080608-201650_Med.jpg" width="500" height="375"></a></p><p>And that&#8217;s it.</p><hr
